.docname {Kubernetes Configuration}
.include {docs}

CrowdVision is designed as a cloud-native, microservices-first application. While Docker Compose is great for quick local testing, Kubernetes (K8s) is the intended environment for staging and production, providing robust scaling, self-healing, and stateful data management.

All Kubernetes operations are managed via `just` recipes from the monorepo root. You do not need to memorise long `kubectl` invocations.

---

## 🚀 The Easy Way: Just Recipes

Assuming you have a running cluster (k3d, k3s, Minikube, or EKS) and your `kubectl` context is set correctly:

.code lang:{bash}
    # First time on a new machine — installs ingress controller, creates namespace,
    # injects secrets from .env, then applies all manifests:
    just k8s-setup

    # Re-apply all manifests after a change (idempotent — safe to run repeatedly):
    just k8s-apply

    # Tear everything down (deletes the namespace and ALL data inside it):
    just k8s-delete

.box type:{warning}
    **`just k8s-delete` is destructive.** All persistent volume data (databases) is permanently deleted. There is no undo. Use `just k8s-stop` instead to pause the cluster without losing data.

### Day-to-Day Operations

.code lang:{bash}
    # Create or rotate all secrets from your .env (idempotent):
    just k8s-secrets

    # Show pods, deployments, services and StatefulSets:
    just k8s-status

    # Tail logs for a service (supports both Deployments and StatefulSets):
    just k8s-logs auth-service

    # Rolling restart for one service (picks up a new :latest image):
    just k8s-restart auth-service

    # Restart all deployments at once (e.g. after rotating secrets):
    just k8s-restart-all

    # Watch a rolling update until completion:
    just k8s-rollout auth-service

---

## ⚙️ Under the Hood: Deployment Order

If you prefer to run commands manually, respect the dependency tree — `k8s-apply` applies them in this exact order:

### 1. Namespace & Config
First, create the isolated namespace and apply shared, non-sensitive configuration.

.code lang:{bash}
    kubectl apply -f k8s/namespace.yml
    kubectl apply -f k8s/configmaps/

### 2. Injecting Secrets
Secrets are created directly from your `.env` file — never committed to the repository.

.code lang:{bash}
    just k8s-secrets

This reads `JWT_SECRET`, `VAPID_PUBLIC_KEY`, `VAPID_PRIVATE_KEY`, `GOOGLE_API_KEY`, `DEEPSEEK_API_KEY`, `GHCR_USERNAME`, `GHCR_TOKEN` and other keys from `.env` and creates the corresponding Kubernetes Secret objects. It is idempotent — safe to run again after rotating keys.

.box type:{warning}
    The namespace must exist before secrets can be created. Always run `kubectl apply -f k8s/namespace.yml` (or `just k8s-setup`) before `just k8s-secrets` in isolation.

### 3. Stateful Services (Databases & Cache)
Microservices crash if their databases are not ready. Apply the `stateful/` directory to spin up MongoDB and Redis.

.code lang:{bash}
    kubectl apply -f k8s/stateful/

*Wait for these pods to reach `Running` state before proceeding.*

### 4. Deployments (Microservices)
Once the data layer is warm, deploy the business logic.

.code lang:{bash}
    kubectl apply -f k8s/deployments/

### 5. Ingress (Routing) & Monitoring

.code lang:{bash}
    kubectl apply -f k8s/ingress.yml
    kubectl apply -f k8s/monitoring/

---

## 🏗️ Image Management

### Building for Production (GHCR)

.code lang:{bash}
    # Build all images tagged for GHCR:
    just k8s-build

    # Push to GHCR (requires: docker login ghcr.io first):
    just k8s-push

    # Build and push in one step:
    just k8s-build-push

### Local k3d Development (No GHCR required)

Build images locally and import them directly into the k3d cluster — no registry needed:

.code lang:{bash}
    just k8s-build          # build all images locally
    just k8s-load           # import into k3d (replaces GHCR pull)
    just k8s-apply          # apply manifests

.box type:{note}
    When using locally loaded images, set `imagePullPolicy: IfNotPresent` in the deployment manifests. With `Always`, Kubernetes will attempt a GHCR pull and ignore the locally loaded image.

### Updating a Single Service

.code lang:{bash}
    # Rebuild (or pull latest), then rolling restart:
    just k8s-restart auth-service

    # Watch the rollout:
    just k8s-rollout auth-service

    # Something broke — instant rollback to the previous version:
    kubectl rollout undo deployment/auth-service -n crowdvision

---

## 🌐 Local DNS Resolution

If running locally via k3d, add the hostname from `k8s/ingress.yml` to your machine's hosts file. Run:

.code lang:{bash}
    just k8s-hosts
    # Prints: 127.0.0.1   crowdvision.local

Open your hosts file as Administrator (Windows: `C:\Windows\System32\drivers\etc\hosts`, Linux/Mac: `/etc/hosts`) and add that line.

---

## 📋 Full Just Reference — Kubernetes

.var {headers}
   - Recipe
   - What it does

.tablebyrows {.headers}
    - - `just k8s-setup`
      - Install nginx ingress + namespace + secrets + all manifests (first-time)
    - - `just k8s-apply`
      - Apply all manifests in dependency order (idempotent)
    - - `just k8s-secrets`
      - Create/update secrets from `.env`
    - - `just k8s-build`
      - Build all Docker images locally, tagged for GHCR
    - - `just k8s-push`
      - Push all images to GHCR
    - - `just k8s-build-push`
      - Build and push in one step
    - - `just k8s-load`
      - Import locally built images into k3d cluster
    - - `just k8s-status`
      - Show all pods/deployments/services in the namespace
    - - `just k8s-logs <service>`
      - Tail live logs for a service
    - - `just k8s-restart <service>`
      - Trigger rolling restart for one service
    - - `just k8s-restart-all`
      - Restart all deployments
    - - `just k8s-rollout <service>`
      - Watch a rolling update until completion
    - - `just k8s-ingress`
      - Install/reinstall the nginx Ingress Controller
    - - `just k8s-validate`
      - Dry-run all manifests without touching the cluster
    - - `just k8s-stop`
      - Pause the cluster (data preserved)
    - - `just k8s-start`
      - Resume a paused cluster
    - - `just k8s-delete`
      - **Destructive** — delete namespace and all data
    - - `just k8s-hosts`
      - Print the line to add to your hosts file
